<main>
  <section class="food-support-hero">
    <h1>Energy & Sustainability in Ladywood</h1>
    <p>
      Understanding the energy challenges facing Ladywood and how community-led
      sustainability initiatives are supporting a fair transition to a low-carbon future.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="food-info">

    <div class="food-info-block">
      <h2>The Energy Transition</h2>
      <p>
        The UK is legally committed to reaching Net Zero greenhouse gas emissions
        by 2050, with targets of reducing emissions by 68% by 2030 and 81% by
        2035. While renewable energy technologies such as solar panels and battery
        storage are expanding rapidly, the transition requires significant quantities
        of critical minerals including lithium, cobalt, nickel and rare earth elements.
      </p>
      <p>
        Creating a sustainable energy system is not only about generating cleaner
        energy but also reducing overall energy demand. A just energy transition
        must balance environmental goals with social equity, ensuring that the move
        to renewable energy does not create new forms of inequality or resource
        exploitation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="food-info-block">
      <h2>Energy Challenges in Ladywood</h2>
      <p>
        The UK has some of the least energy-efficient housing in Europe, resulting
        in high energy bills and increased fuel poverty. In 2021, around 63% of
        properties in the Ladywood Parliamentary Constituency had an Energy
        Performance Certificate (EPC) rating of D or below, indicating poor energy
        efficiency.
      </p>
      <p>
        Fuel poverty remains a significant issue across the area, with approximately
        26.6% of households in the constituency living in fuel poverty. Many
        residents face difficult choices between heating their homes and meeting
        other essential living costs. Around 4.8% of households in the Ladywood
        Ward also have no access to central heating.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="food-info-block">
      <h2>How Energy is Used in Birmingham</h2>
      <p>
        Natural gas remains the dominant source of home heating in Birmingham,
        accounting for around 74% of household heating systems. Electricity
        provides around 12%, while renewable and alternative sources contribute
        a much smaller share.
      </p>
      <p>
        Heating homes remains one of the largest contributors to carbon emissions.
        Improving insulation, upgrading building performance, and retrofitting
        existing housing stock are considered essential steps towards reducing
        emissions while making homes warmer and cheaper to run.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="food-info-block">
      <h2>Renewable Energy & Innovation</h2>
      <p>
        Although the West Midlands does not have access to large-scale offshore
        renewable energy, the region has seen significant growth in distributed
        energy generation. By 2022, more than 2 gigawatts of distributed energy
        capacity had been installed, with solar photovoltaic systems contributing
        the largest share.
      </p>
      <p>
        Tyseley Energy Park in East Birmingham is a major innovation hub focused
        on clean energy technologies. Powered by renewable electricity from a
        waste-wood biomass plant, the site diverts approximately 72,000 tonnes of
        waste wood from landfill and generates enough electricity to power around
        17,000 homes. The park also supports research into energy poverty,
        decarbonisation and sustainable technologies.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="food-info-block">
      <h2>Community Sustainability Initiatives</h2>
      <p>
        CIVIC SQUARE is working with residents to explore neighbourhood-scale
        approaches to retrofit, energy efficiency and decarbonisation. Through
        projects such as the Link Road retrofit programme, communities are
        investigating how streets can collectively transition to low-carbon living
        rather than focusing only on individual households.
      </p>
      <p>
        Community organisations and local businesses are also promoting renewable
        energy adoption, sustainable building practices and energy education.
        Examples include solar energy workshops, retrofit demonstrations, and
        discussions around shared energy infrastructure and water-source heat
        pumps using Birmingham's canal network.
      </p>
    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="food-support-cta">
    <h2>Find energy and sustainability support near you</h2>
    <p>
      Browse local organisations, retrofit projects and sustainability initiatives
      supporting residents across Ladywood and Birmingham.
    </p>
    <a href="/services"
       class="btn-services">
      View Energy Services
    </a>
  </section>

</main>

